Persius then, as he has always been called in modern times rather than by his cognomen, Flaccus, by which his contemporaries knew him, was of equestrian rank, and was born at Volaterrae (volterra), 111 Etruria, on the 4th of December, A.D. 34, the twenty-first year of Tiberius. His father Flaccus died when he was six years old, and he remained under the care of his mother Fulvia Sisennia at his native place, where he went to school till he was twelve years old ². Like Horace, he then was taken to Rome and sent to a grammar and a rhetoric school, the former being under the management of one of the most cele- brated teachers of the day, Remmius Palaemon ³, the other of Virginius Flavus, a rhetorician of eminence, who was afterwards exiled by Nero ⁴. He took the ⁶ toga virilis ⁹ at sixteen, the usual age, and according to custom left school and went, as we should call it, to a private tutor, L.
